# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The site was previously occupied by a mansion known as Alder Hey which the local poor law guardians acquired for use as a children's home in 1910.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The mansion was converted for use as a military hospital in 1914.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the First World War, the United States Army established Camp Hospital 40 on the site, operated by Hospital Unit Q and, subsequently, Unit W.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] American sources commonly refer to Alder Hey as being within Liverpool's Knotty Ash area.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the Second World War, parts of the hospital were again used to treat injured military personnel.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The Liverpool Neonatal Surgical Unit opened at the hospital in 1953.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] This unit was the first neonatal intensive care unit in the United Kingdom.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The opening was largely due to the efforts of Isabella Forshall, a paediatric surgeon.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1990 when Myrtle Street Children's Hospital (founded in 1869 and previously known as Royal Liverpool Children's Hospital) closed, Alder Hey absorbed its A&E department.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital authority was one of 57 such bodies which became an NHS hospital trust in 1991.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Ronald McDonald House, a home for the families of sick children, opened in 1993.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1999 an inquiry was instituted into the Alder Hey organs scandal and to investigate the hospital's practices in respect of removal and retention of human tissue.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The inquiry had far-reaching effects throughout the UK hospital system and provided the impetus for the Human Tissue Act 2004.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In August 2008 the Royal Liverpool Children's NHS Trust became an NHS foundation trust and changed its name to Alder Hey NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Between 2010 and 2014 the number of doctors employed at the trust increased from 269 to 344, while the number of managers increased from 70 to 86.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] At the end of March 2017, the trust was confirmed as one of four additional NHS Global Digital Exemplars, joining the twelve announced in September 2016.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey had its centenary year in 2014, the last year in which it operated from the buildings on its original site.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A new hospital was procured under Private Finance Initiative contract in neighbouring Springfield Park.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The works, which were carried out by Laing O'Rourke at a cost of £187 million, began on 26 March 2013 and the hospital opened in October 2015.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It was Europe's first children's hospital built in a park.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The original Alder Hey buildings were mostly demolished and the land was reclaimed as new parkland for the surrounding community.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Features of the new hospital include access to play areas, natural light and striking views of the park are available wherever possible Children and young people were involved with the design of the new hospital.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A drawing of a flower by teenage patient Eleanor Brogan impressed architects and inspired their final design.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital is a centre of excellence for oncology and muscular dystrophy as well as spinal, heart and brain conditions.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey has Europe's first 3T Intraoperative MRI scanner which is a pioneering technology for neurosurgery, providing surgeons with extremely high resolution images and reducing the need for repeat operations in 90% of cases.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It currently employs about 2,400 staff and treats over 270,000 children from across the UK each year.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey conducts paediatric research into children's medicines, infection, inflammation and oncology.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It has research partners including the University of Liverpool and is a member of Liverpool Health Partners.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey conducts more than 100 clinical research studies on an ongoing basis, ranging from observation to clinical trials.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital is within the National Institute for Health and Care Research's Top 100 Performing Trust's for participation recruitment in 2013/14.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey was a finalist in the Clinical Research Impact category of the 2013 HSJ Awards and in 2014 the innovation team received the Health Service Journal Award for improving health care with technology.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2016 the first phase of a bespoke research, education and innovation centre, Institute in the Park, opened next to Alder Hey in the Park.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In November 2015, the institute hosted a children's health Hackathon in conjunction with Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey Children's Charity supports the work of the hospital.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In addition to NHS funding which covers the running costs of the hospital, Alder Hey relies on charitable support.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Funds are spent directly on initiatives in the hospital to benefit patients.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It funds research initiatives, patient and family enhancements and state of the art medical equipment.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Known as the 'Imagine Appeal' until 2012, Alder Hey Children's Charity is based within the hospital.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] On 14 October 2013 the charity launched a public appeal to raise £30m to fund equipment, facilities and research at Alder Hey's new hospital, Alder Hey in the Park.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In October 2015 the charity announced over £20m had been raised.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2009 charitable support allowed Alder Hey to buy Europe's first 3T intraoperative MRI scanner.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In one charitably funded project, the sound recordist and musician Chris Watson was employed to devise an art project, using bird song recordings made by children to calm other young patients as they received injections and other treatments.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1978, the charity Art For Their Sake, a team of volunteer artists led by founder George Nicholas (now of Ormskirk, England), produced the world's longest mural in the corridors of Alder Hey Children's Hospital.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A Guinness Record was set with a total of 17,963 square feet of murals, and awarded to the hospital in 1986.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Nicholas and his team continued to work on these murals for a period of 30 years, adding to as well as restoring and maintaining, for a total of over 34,000 square feet.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey runs an Arts for Health programme, funded entirely through charitable sources including Alder Hey Children's Charity.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme aims to enhance the experience of being a patient and includes animation projects, music and dance therapy, creative writing, comedy workshops and storytelling.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] An international child health development programme led by Alder Hey clinicians focuses on humanitarian work in developing countries.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme includes provision of immediate medical support, knowledge sharing and involvement with international clinical trials.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme has undertaken work across Africa and Asia, including Pakistan, Malawi, Nepal and India.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the 1990s, Alder Hey was featured in the BBC television series *Children's Hospital*.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2011, chef Heston Blumenthal took to the challenge of changing the dinner menu of Alder Hey Children's Hospital on his televised show, *Heston's Mission Impossible*.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Since September 2012, Alder Hey has regularly featured on the CBBC television series *Operation Ouch!*.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In October 2013, the Care Quality Commission's Intelligent Monitoring system placed Alder Hey in category one, meaning it would be amongst the first hospitals to be inspected under a new style of inspection.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In May 2014, Alder Hey was inspected by the Care Quality Commission and was given the overall rating Requires Improvement.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In June 2015, Alder Hey was re-inspected by the Care Quality Commission and was given the overall rating Good, and was rated Outstanding in the Caring category.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Another inspection took place in 2018, the overall rating was unchanged.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Dame Josephine Williams was appointed Chair of the Trust Board in February 2019.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Louise Shepherd CBE was appointed Chief Executive of the trust in March 2008.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] On 26 January 2023, the Alder Hey Children's Hospital NHS Foundation Trust was granted the Honorary Freedom of the Metropolitan Borough of Sefton.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/altnagelvin-area-hospital] Altnagelvin Area Hospital was the first major hospital built in the United Kingdom after the Second World War and opened in 1960.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/altnagelvin-area-hospital] In February 2003 the hospital was designated as one of the nine acute hospitals in the acute hospital network of Northern Ireland on which healthcare would be focused under the government health policy 'Developing Better Services'.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/altnagelvin-area-hospital] A new renal hemodialysis unit was completed in 2005 and a new laboratory and pharmacy centre, procured under a private finance initiative contract, opened in 2007.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/altnagelvin-area-hospital] A new south wing, designed by HLM Architects and built at a cost of £45 million, was completed in 2010.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/altnagelvin-area-hospital] In January 2011, it was revealed that 18,500 xrays taken in 2009 and 2010 in Altnagelvin's Medical Imaging Department had not been examined by a radiologist.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/altnagelvin-area-hospital] As a result, four patients with cancer had their diagnosis delayed by several months.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/altnagelvin-area-hospital] In March 2011 a political row developed when Health Minister Michael McGimpsey announced the postponement of plans to develop a regional radiotherapy unit at the hospital.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/altnagelvin-area-hospital] The Western Division of the Northern Ireland Ambulance Service (NIAS) is headquartered at the Ambulance Station that is located within the hospital grounds.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/altnagelvin-area-hospital] The hospital is a teaching hospital, and has research and teaching links with Queen's University Belfast, the National University of Ireland, Galway and Ulster University.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/antrim-area-hospital] The **Antrim Area Hospital** is a general hospital in Antrim, County Antrim, Northern Ireland.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/antrim-area-hospital] It is managed by the Northern Health and Social Care Trust.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/antrim-area-hospital] The hospital was commissioned to create extra healthcare capacity in the Antrim area.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/antrim-area-hospital] It was built at a cost of £40 million and was opened by the Prince of Wales in July 1994.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/antrim-area-hospital] In February 2003 it was designated as one of the nine acute hospitals in the acute hospital network of Northern Ireland on which healthcare would be focused under the government health policy 'Developing Better Services'.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/antrim-area-hospital] An extension to the emergency department and an extra 24 bed ward were completed in June 2013.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/ards-community-hospital] The **Ards Community Hospital** is a health facility in Church Street, Newtownards, Northern Ireland.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/ards-community-hospital] It is managed by the South Eastern Health and Social Care Trust.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/ards-community-hospital] The facility has its origins in the Newtownards Union Workhouse which was designed by George Wilkinson and was completed in December 1841.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/ards-community-hospital] It became the Ards District Hospital in 1932 and, after joining the National Health Service in 1948, evolved to become Ards Community Hospital.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/ards-community-hospital] In 2016 the gate lodge for the hospital was refurbished to create a social enterprise café.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/ards-community-hospital] The hospital was used as a location for the filming of *Dublin Murders* in 2018.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/armagh-community-hospital] The **Armagh Community Hospital** is a health facility at Tower Hill, Armagh, Northern Ireland.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/armagh-community-hospital] It is managed by the Southern Health and Social Care Trust.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/armagh-community-hospital] The Armagh Workhouse that it is based within was once the largest such facility in Ulster.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/armagh-community-hospital] The facility has its origins in the Armagh Union Workhouse which was designed by George Wilkinson and was completed in December 1841.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/armagh-community-hospital] After joining the National Health Service as Tower Hill Hospital in 1948, it evolved to become Armagh Community Hospital.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/armagh-community-hospital] The old workhouse infirmary, known as Riverside House, which became the headquarters of the headquarters of the local health and social services board in the 1990s, was marketed for sale in May 2016.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/armagh-community-hospital] During the 2010s, a number of medical departments were closed or withdrawn from Armagh Community Hospital.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/armagh-community-hospital] In 2014, the minor injuries unit was closed temporarily due to the hospital regularly breaching Accident & Emergency time targets set by the Northern Ireland Health and Social Care Board.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/armagh-community-hospital] In 2016, the ophthalmology unit was closed due to shortage of staff and the ear, nose and throat department was closed due to a consultant's retirement.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/armagh-community-hospital] In 2018, following a closure of audiology units and a leaked memo claiming that ophthalmology would not return to the hospital, the Newry and Armagh Social Democratic and Labour Party MLA Justin McNulty accused the hospital's board of engaging in "downgrading by stealth".
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/armagh-community-hospital] This was due to the removals of outpatient units and continued closure of the minor injuries unit.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/banbridge-hospital] The facility has its origins in the Banbridge Union Workhouse which was designed by George Wilkinson and was completed in June 1841.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/banbridge-hospital] It became Banbridge District Hospital in 1932 and, after joining the National Health Service in 1948, it evolved to become Banbridge Hospital.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/banbridge-hospital] Despite some investment in surgical wards in the 1980s, the hospital closed in 1995.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/banbridge-hospital] The old hospital was subsequently demolished and the new Banbridge Health and Care Centre opened on part of the site in 2016.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/bangor-community-hospital] The **Bangor Community Hospital** is a health facility in Castle Street, Bangor, Northern Ireland.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/bangor-community-hospital] The facility, which was designed by Young and MacKenzie in the neo-Georgian style, was opened as Bangor Cottage Hospital in 1910.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/bangor-community-hospital] It was extended in 1925 and, after joining the National Health Service in 1948, it evolved to become Bangor Community Hospital.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/bangor-community-hospital] Despite a local campaign to stop the closure, a 20-bed inpatient ward was closed in June 2015.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children] The **Royal Belfast Hospital for Sick Children** is a specialised government children's hospital and medical centre in Belfast, Northern Ireland.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children] It is managed by the Belfast Health and Social Care Trust and is the only hospital in Northern Ireland dedicated to children.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children] The initial meeting of the founders of the hospital was held at 25 King Street, Belfast, in 1873.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children] A board of management was set up to establish funding and run the resulting medical practice.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children] The main focus was to provide healthcare to the impoverished in a time where government assistance was unknown.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children] The building and general running costs had to come from the public.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children] In deference to this, the original writing which spanned all three storeys on the front of the finished hospital would read: *Erected A.D.1878 By Voluntary – Subscriptions And Donations – Belfast Hospital For Sick Children*.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children] Some of the more prominent founding board members were: Lord O'Neill (President), William Robertson (chairman), Herbert Darbishire (Honorary Secretary), Robert S Craig (Honorary Treasurer), Sir Thomas Dixon (Patron) and Lady Edith Dixon (Patron).
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children] The fundraising process began with a citywide distribution of flyers and by 1876 they had managed to raise £2,000 and the board decided that this was sufficient for work to begin.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children] The new hospital was designed by Thomas Jackson in the Baroque style and built by William McCammond in Queen Street in April 1879.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children] From 1885 onwards several new medical roles were created, including dental specialist, assistant physician, assistant surgeon, external sister, and pathologist.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children] This caused such a strain on funding that the hospital was compelled to stop offering free out-patient medicine as of 1897, opting for a discounted prescription model instead.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children] There was an immediate and catastrophic drop off of out-patient activity and Lord O'Neill repeatedly requested that the decision be reversed.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children] The hospital continued operating despite funding deficits, lack of expansion space, wartime inflation, and the deaths of both Robert O'Neill and Joseph Nelson in 1910.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children] The hospital moved to a new building designed by Tulloch & Fitzsimmons and built by H. & J.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children] Two wards, the Barbour and Musgrave, were decorated with picture tiles depicting nursery rhymes, biblical scenes and the four seasons.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children] Yeames they were manufactured by Minton Hollins.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children] On 20 December 1996, the Irish Republican Army entered the hospital and shot and injured a Royal Ulster Constabulary police officer who was there to guard Democratic Unionist Party secretary Nigel Dodds (who was there visiting his son).
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children] During the incident, a shot hit an empty incubator in the hospital's intensive care unit.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children] The hospital moved to more modern premises on the same site in December 1998.
[src:royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children/royal-belfast-hospital-for-sick-children] In 2013 Finance Minister Simon Hamilton announced that a new children's hospital would be built on the same site at a cost of £250 million.
